{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/how-to-deal-with-infinity-in-python-ab041fc95546", "time": 1683007872.280743, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/how-to-deal-with-infinity-in-python-ab041fc95546/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "How to Deal with Infinity in Python | by Chaitanya Baweja | Towards Data Science", "h1": "How to Deal with Infinity in Python", "description": "There is a variety of ways in which we can represent infinity in Python. We will discuss three of the most popular ones: math.inf, numpy.inf and float('inf')."}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.python.org/downloads/release/python-360/", "anchor_text": "Python 3.6", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "https://numpy.org/", "anchor_text": "numpy", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "https://numpy.org/devdocs/reference/constants.html", "anchor_text": "Numpy", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/28940/why-is-infty-cdot-0-not-clearly-equal-to-0", "anchor_text": "Infinity * Zero paradox", "paragraph_index": 12}, {"url": "https://medium.com/@chaitanyabaweja1", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 18}], "all_paragraphs": ["\u2018We are merely explorers of infinity in the pursuit of absolute perfection.\u2019 \u2014 G.H. Hardy", "Many people think that Infinity is just a very large number. But in reality, Infinity is the idea of something being endless and without any bounds.", "Since the early ages, mathematicians have gambled with this concept of endlessness. As John Green wrote in his book The Fault in Our Stars,", "\u201cEndlessness is a really strange idea in a universe that is defined by its endings.\u201d", "Infinity has many desirable properties for algorithmic design. The most popular being:", "Every number is smaller than positive infinity and bigger than negative infinity.", "There is a variety of ways in which we can represent infinity in Python. We will discuss three of the most popular ones below.", "Code written in this article was tested on Python 3.6. The only non-standard library that you need here is numpy. You can install it quite simply using:", "We\u2019ll create two variables and initialize them with positive and negative infinity.", "Another popular method for representing infinity is using Python\u2019s math module. Take a look:", "Numpy also has its own definitions for infinite values. We can also create arrays filled with infinity values. The code is shown below:", "The math module provides an isinf() method which allows us to easily check for infinite values in Python. It returns a Boolean value. Take a look:", "Most arithmetic operations on infinite numbers result in other infinite numbers. The Infinity * Zero paradox makes for a very interesting dinner conversation. At-least I hope it does. I have yet to try it.", "Infinity is often used in optimization problems. For example, in Shortest Path algorithms, we need to compare the current distance with the best or least distance so far.", "We initialize unknown distances with positive infinity. No matter what distance you enter in the program, no number can be greater than this representation of infinity.", "We discussed multiple ways of representing infinite values in Python.", "I personally use the math.inf method for defining a single infinite number. This is because this method is usually the fastest of all three. Also, math is a standard library and is already a part of most of my codes.", "But like always, Numpy becomes faster when we start dealing with arrays:", "I hope you found this tutorial useful! You can find other stories from me here.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Machine Learning Engineer | Python | Data Analytics | Economics | Physics"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fab041fc95546&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav------------------